Heart murmurs are sounds — such as whooshing or swishing — made by turbulent blood in or near your heart. Your doctor can hear these sounds with a stethoscope. Episodes are usually followed by a vivid recollection of a dream that is consistent with the aggressive behavior. This condition primarily affects adult males. (From Adams et al., Principles of Neurology, 6th ed, p393)

The patient stands with the feet placed together and balance and is asked to close his or her eyes. A loss of balance upon eye closure is a positive Romberg sign and is interpreted as indicating a deficit in proprioception.

The Romberg test is positive if the patient begins to sway when standing erect with eyes closed.  In general, patients with cerebellar problems will not be able to stand with feet together even with eyes open.  Swaying that begins when the patient closes their eyes suggests a problem with proprioception in the lower extremities.

group.rdfs_comment: Tapping over the carpal tunnel produces pain in the first, second, and third fingers.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Tinel's sign is positive when tapping over the carpal tunnel elicits symptoms in the distribution of the median nerve.
A moderate degree of visual loss
In cases of sensori-neural hearing loss, the sound lateralizes to the good ear.
n cases of sensori-neural hearing loss, the sound lateralizes to the good ear.

An abdominal reflex is a superficial neurological reflex stimulated by stroking of the abdomen around the umbilicus. It can be helpful in determining the level of a central nervous system (CNS) lesion. Being a superficial reflex, it is polysynaptic (involving multiple connections between nerves)
A disorder characterized by involvement of the abducens nerve (sixth cranial nerve) with limitation of abduction of the eye laterally.
Impairment in the function of the sixth cranial nerve which causes weakness of the lateral rectus muscle which turns the eye outward.
An abnormailty of mood or affect.
Any involuntary abnormal movement such as tremor, chorea, hemiballismus, athetosis, or myoclonus.

An abnormality of the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR). The VOR attempts to keep the image stable on the retina. Ideally passive or active head movements in one direction are compensated for by eye movements of equal magnitude.
Disturbance of eyesight
Absence of facial sweating.

A typical absence seizure is a generalized seizure with abrupt onset and offset of altered awareness which can vary in severity (see specific syndromes). Memory for events during the seizures is usually impaired although there may be some retained awareness particularly for adolescents. Clonic movements of eyelids. A seizure disorder usually occurring in childhood characterized by rhythmic electrical brain discharges of generalized onset. Clinical features include a sudden cessation of ongoing activity usually without loss of postural tone. Rhythmic blinking of the eyelids or lip smacking frequently accompanies the SEIZURES. The usual duration is 5-10 seconds
Lack of contraction of abdominal muscles in the quadrant of the abdomen that is stimulated by scraping the skin tangential to or toward the umbilicus.

group.rdfs_comment: No response to noxious stimulation around the anus.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A noxious or tactile stimulus will cause a wink contraction of the anal sphincter muscles and also flexion.
Absence of normal anal tone.
Absence of the deep tendon reflex at the ankle which is usually elicited by striking the Achilles tendon with a reflex hammer.
Absence of the biceps reflex which is generally elicited by striking the biceps tendon in the antecubital fossae with a reflex hammer.
Inability to sense body position using proprioception.

The reflex is consensual: Normally light that is directed in one eye produces pupil constriction in both eyes. The consensual response is the change in pupil size in the eye opposite to the eye to which the light is directed (e.g., if the light is shone in the right eye, the left pupil also constricts consensually). Failure of a pupil to constrict when light is shown in the opposite eye is a absent consensual reflex.
The corneal reflex is elicited by touching the cornea with a wisp of cotton or tissue.  The afferent loop is ove V1 of the trigeminal nerve and the efferent loop is over the facial nerve.
Inability to elicit deep tendon reflexes.

An abnormality of the reflex that controls the diameter of the pupil, in response to the intensity of light that falls on the retina of the eye. If pupil fails to constrict to light shown to the same eye, the direct reflex is absent.
Absence of the knee jerk reflex, which can normally be elicited by tapping the patellar tendon with a reflex hammer just below the patella.
Absence of left corneal reflex.
Failure of pupil to constrictd with near vision.
A finding indicating the complete absence of neurological reflexes
Absence of right corneal reflex.
A loss of sensation in any sensory modality such as temperature, vibration, joint position sense, pin prick sensation, or light touch.

Absence of the supinator reflex, also known as the radial reflex or the brachioradialis reflex, which is elicited by gently striking the radius bone with a reflex hammer and observing contraction of the brachioradialis muscle.
Unable to elicit deep tendon reflex.
Absence of the triceps reflex which is usually elicited by striking the triceps tendon with a reflex hammer.
Poverty of behavior and speech output, lack of initiative, loss of emotional responses, psychomotor slowing, and prolonged speech latency.
Complete color blindness, a complete inability to distinguish colors. Affected persons cannot perceive colors, but only shades of gray.

group.rdfs_comment: Features of the condition include blackheads or whiteheads, pimples, oily skin
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Acne, also known as acne vulgaris, is a long-term skin condition that occurs when dead skin cells and oil from the skin clog hair follicles. Typical features of the condition include blackheads or whiteheads, pimples, oily skin, and possible scarring.It primarily affects skin with a relatively high number of oil glands, including the face, upper part of the chest, and back. The resulting appearance can lead to anxiety, reduced self-esteem, and, in extreme cases, depression or thoughts of suicide
Non-heritable difficulty in distinguishing colors.
Sudden appearance of disease manifestations over a short period of time.

Adenoma sebaceum is a misnamed cutaneous disorder consisting of angiofibromas that begin in childhood (generally present between 2–5 years of age) and appear clinically as red papules on the face especially on the nasolabial folds, cheek and chin; mostly thought to be acne not responding to treatment. Adenoma sebaceum may at times be associated with tuberous sclerosis. Gradually the papules become more prominent with time and persist throughout life. Cosmetic removal by argon or pulse dye laser or scalpel is indicated
The pupil responds consensually but not directly to light--so-called positive swinging flashlight test suggesting an afferent defect in the diseased eye.

An aberrant pupillary response characterized by (i) Constriction of pupils of both eyes when the light stimulus is applied to the normal eye, and (ii) Dilatation of pupils of both eyes when the light stimulus is rapidly transferred from the normal eye (after brief light exposure to the normal eye) to the affected eye.  Both pupils dilate when the light is switched to the affected eye.
Complete or severe loss of the subjective sense of taste, Inability to taste.
Aggressive behavior can denote verbal aggression, physical aggression against objects, physical aggression against people, and may also include aggression towards oneself.
Episodes or outbursts of aggressive behavior towards others including aggressive verbal or physical behaviors.

A condition in which a person is unable to relax and be still. The person may be very tense and irritable, and become easily annoyed by small things. He or she may be eager to have an argument, and be unwilling to work with caregivers to make the situation better.

Inability to recognize objects not because of sensory deficit but because of the inability to combine components of sensory impressions into a complete pattern. Thus, agnosia is a neurological condition which results in an inability to know, to name, to identify, and to extract meaning from visual, auditory, or tactile impressions.

group.rdfs_comment: Could not recognize objects by touch.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Inability to recognize the form of objects by touch without visual input. That is, an impairment in the recognition of objects based only on based on the texture, size, weight and three-dimensional form of the object in the absence of any major somatosensory deficit.

group.rdfs_comment: Unable to build mental representation of the environment.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Topographical disorientation, also known as topographical agnosia and topographagnosia, is the inability to orient oneself in one's surroundings as a result of focal brain damage. This disability may result from the inability to make use of selective spatial information (e.g., environmental landmarks) or to orient by means of specific cognitive strategies such as the ability to form a mental representation of the environment, also known as a cognitive map. It may be part of a syndrome known as visuospatial dysgnosia.

group.rdfs_comment: Impaired ability to recognize objects presented visually
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Difficulty in recognizing objects by visual input in absence of sensorial visual impairment
The inability to recognize letters or numbers traced on the palm of the hand despite adequate sensation.

group.rdfs_comment: Unable to use pen or pencil
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: An acquired inability to write.
Bone conduction better than air conduction.
A disorder characterized by an uncomfortable feeling of inner restlessness and inability to stay still; this is a side effect of some psychotropic drugs.

A syndrome characterized by a silent and inert state without voluntary motor activity despite preserved sensorimotor pathways and vigilance. Bilateral frontal lobe dysfunction involving the anterior cingulate gyrus and related brain injuries are associated with this condition. This may result in impaired abilities to communicate and initiate motor activities.
An acquired type of sensory aphasia where damage to the brain leads to the loss of the ability to read.

group.rdfs_comment: Pain induced by a non painful stimulus
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Allodynia is the elicitation of pain by stimuli that are normally not painful.
An abnormality of mental functioning including various affective, behavioural, cognitive and perceptual abnormalities.
An altered state of consciousness (ASC), also called altered state of mind or mind alteration, is any condition which is significantly different from a normal waking state.
A field defect in either the upper or lower visual field that has a horizontal border.

An altitudinal visual field defect is a condition in which there is defect in the superior or inferior portion of the visual field that respects the horizontal midline. The altitudinal defect can be unilateral or bilateral
A transient visual disturbance that is typically caused by a circulatory, ocular or neurological underlying condition
absence of menses for three months or more.
Systematic and extensive loss of memory caused by organic or psychological factors. The loss may be temporary or permanent, and may involve old or recent memories.
The inability to recognize musical tones or to reproduce them.

Pure anarthria is a rare disorder commonly defined as a total inability to articulate speech in the absence of any deficit both of auditory comprehension and of written language. It can follow either cortical, subcortical, or brain stem lesions. Anarthria should be kept separate from mutism (inability or unwillingness to speak in the absence of any brain lesion capable of affect the articulatory planning), as well as from dysarthria (a speech disorder due to weakness or incoordination of speech muscles).
An absence of sweating.
Anisocoria, or unequal pupil size, may represent a benign physiologic variant or a manifestation of disease.
Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Ankle clonus is tested by rapidly flexing the foot upward.
A language dysfunction characterized by the inability to name people and objects that are correctly perceived.
clinical manifestation consisting of a physiopathological lack or loss of appetite accompanied by an aversion to food and the inability to eat.

An inability to perceive odors. This is a general term describing inability to smell arising in any part of the process of smelling from absorption of odorants into the nasal mucous overlying the olfactory epithelium, diffusion to the cilia, binding to olfactory receptor sites, generation of action potentials in olfactory neurons, and perception of a smell.
A condition in which a person who suffers illness or disability seems unaware of or denies the existence of the illness or disabilit
Feelings or emotions of dread, apprehension, and impending disaster but not disabling as with ANXIETY DISORDERS.
Lack of emotion or emotional expression; a disorder of motivation that persists over time.

group.rdfs_comment: Impairment in comprehension, naming, repetition, and expression.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Cognitive disorder marked by an impaired ability to comprehend or express language in its written or spoken form; caused by diseases which affect the language areas of the dominant hemisphere; general categories include receptive, expressive, and mixed forms of aphasia

An aphasia characterized by impairment of expressive LANGUAGE (speech, writing, signs) and relative preservation of receptive language abilities (i.e., comprehension). This condition is caused by lesions of the motor association cortex in the FRONTAL LOBE (BROCA AREA and adjacent cortical and white matter regions).

Impairment in the comprehension of speech and meaning of words, both spoken and written, and of the meanings conveyed by their grammatical relationships in sentences. It is caused by lesions that primarily affect Wernicke's area, which lies in the posterior perisylvian region of the temporal lobe of the dominant hemisphere.
A mild form of aphasia with prominent problems in word retrieval and naming.  Repetition and comprehension are usually spared.  Speech is fluent.
Aphasia, apraxia, alexia, and agnosia are commonly grouped together as higher cortical functions.

A type of fluent aphasia characterized by an impaired ability to repeat one and two word phrases, despite retained comprehension. This condition is associated with dominant hemisphere lesions involving the arcuate fasciculus (a white matter projection between Broca's and Wernicke's areas) and adjacent structures. Like patients with Wernicke aphasia (APHASIA, WERNICKE), patients with conduction aphasia are fluent but commit paraphasic errors during attempts at written and oral forms of communication.
A severe form of aphasia with disturbances of both comprehension, repetition, and expression.  Naming is impaired.
A form of aphasia with both deficits in expression and comprehension.
A form of aphasia with relatively preserved naming and repetition but deficits in comprehension of complex grammatical structures.
Subcortical aphasia refers to language impairments that develop in association with damage-affecting regions other than the cerebral hemisphere, usually the left thalamus and basal ganglia.
Transcortical aphasia is a form of aphasia with preserved ability to repeat words and phrases.

group.rdfs_comment: loss of ability to perform skilled movements.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: loss of ability to perform familiar, purposeful movements in the absence of paralysis or other neural sensorimotor impairment.

Constructional apraxia is characterized by an inability or difficulty to build, assemble, or draw objects.  Apraxia is a neurological disorder in which people are unable to perform tasks or movements even though they understand the task, are willing to complete it, and have the physical ability to perform the movements. Constructional apraxia may be caused by lesions in the parietal lobe following stroke or it may serve as an indicator for Alzheimer's disease.

Dressing apraxia is a syndrome of the right (incorrectly defined as minor) hemisphere, indicating the incapacity of effectuating the acts of dressing correctly (for example passing the head in the sleeve or dressing trousers at the inverse etc…). However this difficulty should not be explained by a primary motor or sensory deficit or by a general attention failure (as it can be observed in patients with dementia, delirium or with a severe frontal syndrome). Interestingly, several cases reports of patients with pure dressing apraxia have been published, without the evidence of the co-presence of other forms of apraxia or other significant deficits in other cognitive spheres.

group.rdfs_comment: Was not able to show how to seal an envelope.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: An inability to perform complex sequential motor acts due to brain disease.

group.rdfs_comment: Was not able to show how to wave good bye or brush teeth.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A form of apraxia characterized by an acquired inability to carry out a complex motor activity despite the ability to mentally formulate the action. This condition has been attributed to a disruption of connections between the dominant parietal cortex and supplementary and premotor cortical regions in both hemispheres.

group.rdfs_comment: Unable to blow out candles or whistle
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Oral apraxia, for example, is an inability to voluntarily control the muscles used to move the mouth
Absence of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.
Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the lower limbs.

group.rdfs_comment: Absent reflexes in the upper limb.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the upper limbs.
The reduced swinging of the arms while walking usually indicates an extra-pyramidal motor disorder such as Parkinson disease.
Sensation of unpleasant feeling indicating potential or actual damage to some body structure felt in one or more joints. A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in a joint.

group.rdfs_comment: weakness that began in legs and spread to the arms
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Weakness and numbness that begins in the lower limbs and ascends to the upper limbs over time. Guillain-Barre syndrome often begins with tingling and weakness starting in your feet and legs and spreading to your upper body and arms.
An abnormal accumulation of serous fluid in the abdominal cavity

Hypomelanic macules ("ash leaf spots") are present in about 90% of people with tuberous sclerosis. These small white or lighter patches of skin may appear anywhere on the body, and are caused by a lack of melanin. They are usually the only visible sign of tuberous sclerosis at birth.
Astasia-abasia refers to the inability to either stand or walk in a normal manner. Astasia refers to the inability to stand upright unassisted. Abasia refers to lack of motor coordination in walking.

group.rdfs_comment: Did not recognize objects placed in hand
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Inability to recognize the form of objects by touch without visual input. That is, an impairment in the recognition of objects based only on based on the texture, size, weight and three-dimensional form of the object in the absence of any major somatosensory deficit.

group.rdfs_comment: the inability to maintain sustained posture with subsequent brief, shock-like, involuntary movements
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A clinical sign indicating a lapse of posture and is usually manifest by a bilateral flapping tremor at the wrist, metacarpophalangeal, and hip joints.
A smile in which both corners of the mouth do not elevate symmetrically, often a sign of facial weakness.
Ataxia is the presence of uncoordinated, imprecise, and inaccurate movements. Ataxia is the cardinal sign of cerebellar disease.
Ataxia that affects primarily the limbs and can be elicited by the finger-to-nose test or heel-knee-shin test or rapid alternating movements.

Cerebellar ataxia refers to ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum. This causes a variety of elementary neurological deficits including asynergy (lack of coordination between muscles, limbs and joints), dysmetria (lack of ability to judge distances that can lead to under- or overshoot in grasping movements), and dysdiadochokinesia (inability to perform rapid movements requiring antagonizing muscle groups to be switched on and off repeatedly).
Ataxia that is of mild severity.  See definition of ataxia.
Difficulty reaching to visually guided goals in peripheral vision, with the deficit leaves voluntary eye movements largely unaffected.

group.rdfs_comment: Proprioceptive deficits may produce truncal or appendicular ataxia that resembles cerebellar ataxia.  The Romberg test may disclose that the truncal ataxia is due to proprioceptive as opposed to cerebellar dysfunction if the patient begins to sway with feet together when the eyes are closed.

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Truncal ataxia is manifested by swaying while standing or walking.  Its origins may reflect dysfunction of cerebellar or proprioceptive systems.
A movement disorder consisting of slow, involuntary, and nonpurposeful writhing movements that usually affect the upper limbs.
Muscle atrophy in the small muscles of the hand.
Disorders of sustained attention. A failure to attend to stimuli.
Inattention to sounds in one sphere of space or in one ear.

These are some of the characteristics of ASD: problems with social interaction with others. unusual interest in objects. need for sameness. great variation in abilities. under or over reaction to one or more of the five senses: sight, touch, taste, smell, or hearing. repeated actions or body movements. Delayed or abnormal language.
Automatic, mechanical, and apparently undirected behavior which is outside of conscious control.

group.rdfs_comment: Unable to orient oneself to ones own body parts
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Autotopagnosia is a form of agnosia, characterized by an inability to localize and orient different parts of the body.The disorder has also been referred to as "body-image agnosia" or "somatotopagnosia." Somatotopagnosia has been argued to be a better suited term to describe the condition. While autotopagnosia emphasizes the deficiencies in localizing only one's own body parts and orientation, somatotopagnosia also considers the inability to orient and recognize the body parts of others or representations of the body (e.g., manikins, diagrams)
A  finding of impaired balance which may include unsteadiness, swaying, or falling.

group.rdfs_comment: Electric shock like sensation down spine on neck flexion
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Lhermitte's sign (also known as Lhermitte's phenomenon also referred to as the barber chair phenomenon is the name which describes an electric shock-like sensation that occurs on flexion of the neck. This sensation radiates down the spine, often into the legs, arms, and sometimes to the trunk.
Excessive closing or blinking of the eyes.

group.rdfs_comment: Bilateral blowing sounds heard over both carotid arteries.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Bruit heard over both carotid arteries.
Both pupils are dilated and unreactive to light.
A foot drop of both feet.
Weakness of both hands
Hearing loss in both ears.
A loss of vison in both hemifields of vision, often a prelude to cortical blindness.
Bilateral sensori-neural hearing loss.
Rigidity that is bilateral.
Sensorineural hearing loss in both ears.
A focal dystonia that affects the muscles of the eyelids and brow, associated with involuntary recurrent spasm of both eyelids
Loss of vision in one eye.

Inability to see or the loss or absence of perception of visual stimuli; condition may be the result of eye, optic nerve, optic chiasm or brain diseases effecting the visual pathways or occipital lobe.

group.rdfs_comment: Loss of vision in both eyes
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A loss of vision in both eyes.

The corneal reflex, also known as the blink reflex, is an involuntary blinking of the eyelids elicited by stimulation of the cornea (such as by touching or by a foreign body), though could result from any peripheral stimulus.
Abnormal excessive blinking
Loss of normal affect, affect that is flat and lack variation.
Restricted range of emotional expressiveness.
group.rdfs_seeAlso: emotional indifference; affect blunt; restricted range of emotion; emotional blunting

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Indistinct borders to the optic disc suggesting papilledema
A disorder characterized by visual perception of unclear or fuzzy images.
Air  conduction better than bone conduction.
Abnormal slowness of movement, which is often a symptom of neurological disorders, particularly Parkinson's disease.
An overactive ankle reflex
An overactive biceps reflex
Overactive finger reflexes

To elicit the jaw jerk, the examiner places an index finger over the jaw or chin, holding the mouth partly open, then gently taps the examiner's finger with the reflex hammer.  The the brisk jaw jerk may indicate a state of generalized hyperreflexia due to a supranuclear lesion such as stroke or ALS.
An abnormally active knee reflex.
Overactive knee reflexes

Tendon reflexes that are noticably more active than usual (conventionally denoted 3+ on clinical examnation). Brisk reflexes may or may not indicate a neurological lesion. They are distinguished from hyperreflexia by the fact that hyerreflexia is characterized by hyperactive repeating (clonic) reflexes, which are considered to be always abnormal.
An abnormally active radial or supinator reflex.
group.rdfs_seeAlso: brisk radial reflex; brisk brachioradialis reflex

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: overactive deep tendon reflexes
Overactive triceps reflex.

The test involves monitoring internal/external anal sphincter contraction in response to squeezing the glans penis or clitoris, or tugging on an indwelling Foley catheter. This reflex can also be tested electrophysiologically, by stimulating the penis or vulva and recording from the anal sphincter. This testing modality is used in intraoperative neurophysiology monitoring to verify the function of sensory and motor sacral roots as well as the conus medullaris.[1]
An unpleasant sensation of pain as if the area has been burned.

Cafe au lait spots, or café au lait macules, are flat, hyperpigmented birthmarks. The name café au lait is French for "coffee with milk" and refers to their light-brown color. Cafe au lait lesions with rough borders (“coast of Maine”) may be seen in McCune-Albright syndrome.  In contrast, Café au lait lesions of neurofibromatosis have smooth borders (“coast of California").
Muscle hypertrophy affecting the calf muscles.
Shoulder shrug is generally considered an action of the trapezius muscle, although the levator scapulae contributes to this action.

Cardiomyopathy is a disease of the heart muscle that makes it harder for your heart to pump blood to the rest of your body. Cardiomyopathy can lead to heart failure.The main types of cardiomyopathy include dilated, hypertrophic and restrictive cardiomyopathy.
Symptoms related to the heart or vascular system such as palpitations, chest pain, hypertension, or hypotension.

group.rdfs_comment: Blowing sound heard over carotid artery.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A carotid bruit is a vascular murmur sound (bruit) heard over the carotid artery area on auscultation during systole.

group.rdfs_comment: attacks of weakness with falling to ground
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: transient attack of weakness precipitated by emotional excitement; patient falls as if struck down.
A cataract is an opacity or clouding that develops in the crystalline lens of the eye or in its capsule

A neuropsychiatric disorder characterized by one or more of the following essential features: immobility, mutism, negativism (active or passive refusal to follow commands), mannerisms, stereotypies, posturing, grimacing, excitement, echolalia, echopraxia, muscular rigidity, and stupor; sometimes punctuated by sudden violent outbursts, panic, or hallucinations.
Reduced muscle tone secondary to an abnormality of the central nervous system
A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) located between the central point of fixation and the blind spot with a roughly horizontal oval shape.
Sensory loss in the distribution of a cervical root.
Interference with respiration by compression or obstruction of the larynx or trachea.

Chorea (Greek for dance) refers to widespread arrhythmic involuntary movements of a forcible, jerky and restless fashion. It is a random-appearing sequence of one or more discrete involuntary movements or movement fragments. Movements appear random because of variability in timing, duration or location. Each movement may have a distinct start and end. However, movements may be strung together and thus may appear to flow randomly from one muscle group to another. Chorea can involve the trunk, neck, face, tongue, and extremities.
Involuntary movements characterized by both athetosis (inability to sustain muscles in a fixed position) and chorea (widespread jerky arrhythmic movements).
Slow, creeping onset, slow progress and long continuance of disease manifestations.

The ciliospinal reflex (pupillary-skin reflex) consists of dilation of the ipsilateral pupil in response to pain applied to the neck, face, and upper trunk. If the right side of the neck is subjected to a painful stimulus, the right pupil dilates (increases in size 1-2mm from baseline). This reflex is absent in Horner's syndrome and lesions involving the cervical sympathetic fibers. The enhanced ciliospinal reflex in asymptomatic patients with cluster headache is due to preganglionic sympathetic mechanisms.

group.rdfs_comment: Resistance to extension like a clasp knife.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: clasp-knife spasticity a type of increased muscle tone due to a pyramidal tract lesion, in which abnormally increased resistance to passive stretch of a muscle abruptly decreases; typically, this appears near the end of the range of joint excursion.

group.rdfs_comment: Stretch of the achilles tendon produced clonus.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A series of rhythmic and involuntary muscle contractions (at a frequency of about 5 to 7 Hz) that occur in response to an abruptly applied and sustained stretch.

Clouding of consciousness (also known as brain fog or mental fog) is when a person is slightly less wakeful or aware than normal. ... They are not as aware of time or their surroundings and find it difficult to pay attention. People describe this subjective sensation as their mind being "foggy
Movements that are imprecise or inaccurate.
Diminished or impaired mental and/or intellectual function
Symptoms related to cognitive behavior such as language, memory, reasoning, abstract thought, and visual spatial manipulations.

A type of rigidity in which a muscle responds with cogwheellike jerks to the use of constant force in bending the limb (i.e., it gives way in little, repeated jerks when the muscle is passively stretched).
fall down and become unconscious, typically through illness or injury.
fall down and become unconscious, typically through illness or injury.

A profound state of unconsciousness associated with depressed cerebral activity from which the individual cannot be aroused. Coma generally occurs when there is dysfunction or injury involving both cerebral hemispheres or the brain stem reticular formation.
Complete hearing loss.
Complete hearing loss.

A type of focal-onset seizure characterized by impaired awareness. Awareness during a seizure is defined as the patient being fully aware of themself and their environment throughout the seizure, even if immobile. If awareness is impaired at any point during the seizure, the seizure is a focal impaired awareness seizure. The degree of loss of awareness may vary.
An inability to comprehend emotion as conveyed by the prosody of speech.

An absolute or relative decrease in retinal sensitivity extending from edge (periphery) of the visual field in a concentric pattern. The visual field is the area that is perceived simultaneously by a fixating eye
Giving untruthful answers to questions about situations or events that are not recalled due to loss of memory. Confabulation is not a conscious attempt to deceive.
A mental state characterized by bewilderment, emotional disturbance, lack of clear thinking, and perceptual disorientation

Conjunctival hyperemia is a conjunctival reaction that appears as dilation and redness of the conjunctival vessels. The pattern of hyperemia often appears with the greatest redness at the fornices and fades moving toward the limbus.
A group of symptoms that affect an individual's general well being. Representative examples include fever, chills, fatigue, weakness, and weight loss.
Irregular and infrequent or difficult evacuation of the bowels.

An absolute or relative decrease in retinal sensitivity extending from edge (periphery) of the visual field in a concentric pattern. The visual field is the area that is perceived simultaneously by a fixating eye.  Narrowed or reduced visual field.

Convergence‐retraction nystagmus is an irregular, jerky nystagmus in which both eyeballs rhythmically converge and retract into the orbit, particularly on attempting an upward gaze.1 In humans it is seen as part of Parinaud's syndrome, also known as dorsal midbrain syndrome, in which a lesion of dorsally located
A disorder whose predominant feature is a loss or alteration in physical functioning that suggests a physical disorder but that is actually a direct expression of a psychological conflict or need.
Coordination is the ability to perform complex movements precisely and accurately.
Disorder occurring in the central or peripheral area of the cornea. The usual degree of transparency becomes relatively opaque
A form of loss of vision caused by damage to the visual cortex rather than a defect in the eye.
A sudden, audible expulsion of air from the lungs through a partially closed glottis, preceded by inhalation
A description or characterization of the duration of a disease.

The major part of the spinal accessory nerve (11th cranial nerve) innervates the trapezius muscle and the sternocleidomastoid muscle.  Weakness of these muscles maybe supranuclear, nuclear, or infranuclear in origin.  A special visceral efferent branch to the vagus nerve is not tested clinically.
The twelfth cranial nerve is purely motor and supplies the tongue.
Diseases of the first cranial (olfactory) nerve, which usually feature anosmia or other alterations in the sense of smell and taste.
Cranial nerve 2, 3,4, and 6 are involved in vision.  Eye movements, pupillary reactions, visual fields, and visual acuity may all be affected.
Findings related to the fifth cranial nerve; the trigeminal nerve.

Diseases of the facial nerve or nuclei. Pontine disorders may affect the facial nuclei or nerve fascicle. The nerve may be involved intracranially, along its course through the petrous portion of the temporal bone, or along its extracranial course. Clinical manifestations include facial muscle weakness, loss of taste from the anterior tongue, hyperacusis, and decreased lacrimation.

Pathological processes of the vestibulocochlear nerve, including the branches of cochlear and vestibular nerve. Common examples are vestibular neuritis, cochlear neuritis, and acoustic neuroma. Clinical signs are varying degree of hearing loss, vertigo, and tinnitus.
A finding referable to the vagus nerve.
Deficits that arise from dysfunction of one of the twelve cranial nerves.
An abnormality due to abnormal cranial nerve reflexes.

Traumatic injuries involving the cranium and intracranial structures. Injuries may be classified by whether or not the skull is penetrated (i.e., penetrating vs. nonpenetrating) or whether there is an associated hemorrhage.

The cremasteric reflex is a superficial (i.e., close to the skin's surface) reflex observed in human males. This reflex is elicited by lightly stroking or poking the superior and medial (inner) part of the thigh—regardless of the direction of stroke. The normal response is an immediate contraction of the cremaster muscle that pulls up the testis ipsilaterally (on the same side of the body). The reflex utilizes sensory and motor fibers from two different nerves. When the inner thigh is stroked, sensory fibers of the ilioinguinal nerve are stimulated. These activate the motor fibers of the genital branch of the genitofemoral nerve which causes the cremaster muscle to contract and elevate the testis

Superficial reflexes are motor responses to scraping of the skin. They are graded simply as present or absent, although markedly asymmetrical responses should be considered abnormal as well. These reflexes are quite different from the muscle stretch reflexes in that the sensory signal has to not only reach the spinal cord, but also must ascend the cord to reach the brain. The motor limb then has to descend the spinal cord to reach the motor neurons. As can be seen from the description, this is a polysynaptic reflex. This can be abolished by severe lower motor neuron damage or destruction of the sensory pathways from the skin that is stimulated. However, the utility of superficial reflexes is that they are decreased or abolished by conditions that interrupt the pathways between the brain and spinal cord (such as with spinal cord damage).

In many patients complex types of walking, such as walking backwards and running are paradoxically less impaired than walking forward and may seem completely unaffected. Sensory tricks, for instance, if the affected individual rests a hand on his or her neck, may improve or even normalize dystonic gait in some patients.

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Partial or complete loss of vision in one half of the visual field of one or both eyes.
A loss of vision in both temporal visual fields.
Loss of vision in one half of the field of vision in both eyes.  Homonymous suggests that the field defect is equal in both eyes.
A loss of vision in the nasal visual field.

Hemiballismus is a rare movement disorder that is caused primarily by damage to various areas in the basal ganglia. Hemiballismus is usually characterized by involuntary flinging motions of the extremities. The movements are often violent and have wide amplitudes of motion. They are continuous and random and can involve proximal and/or distal muscles on one side of the body, while some cases even include the facial muscles. The more a patient is active, the more the movements increase. With relaxation comes a decrease in movements.
A lack of sweating on one side of the face.

Recurrent clonic contraction of facial muscles, restricted to one side. It may occur as a manifestation of compressive lesions involving the seventh cranial nerve (FACIAL NERVE DISEASES), during recovery from BELL PALSY, or in association with other disorders.

group.rdfs_comment: Weakness of the arm and leg on one side of the body
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.
Weakness of left arm and leg
Weakness of right arm and leg
Paralysis (complete loss of muscle function) in the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.
Severe paralysis of the left arm and leg.
Severe weakness of right arm and leg.

group.rdfs_comment: Hyperesthesias on one side of the body
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Dysesthesias or hyperesthesias on one side of the body.

group.rdfs_comment: Sensory loss on one side of the body.

Loss of sensation to all modalities on one side of the body.
Loss of pain and temperature sensation on one side of the body.
Loss of light touch sensation on one side of the body
Hemisensory loss for vibration.
Failure to respond to stimuli on one side of space or one side of the body.
abnormal enlargement of the liver.
A loss of vision in the hemifields of both eyes in which the extent and size of visual loss differs by eye.
An involuntary spasm of the diaphragm and respiratory organs, with a sudden closure of the glottis and a characteristic sound like that of a cough.
An abnormal increase in the pitch (frequency) of the voice
An abnormal gait with foot lifted high from the ground to compensate for a foot drop.
Hip flexor weakness.
A history of falling in the recent past.

If you are hoarse, your voice will sound breathy, raspy, or strained, or will be softer in volume or lower in pitch. Your throat might feel scratchy. Hoarseness is often a symptom of problems in the vocal folds of the larynx
Thinking about ending or making plans to end another's life.
A quadrant of vision loss that is homonymous in both eyes.
Double vision in which images are side by side on horizontal plane.
Persistent or frequent angry feelings; anger or irritability in response to minor slights and insults.
Hyperactivity means having increased movement, impulsive actions, and a shorter attention span, and being easily distracted.
Abnormally increased perception of sound.
Sounds seem unnaturally loud in the left ear.
Sounds that seem too loud in the right ear.
excessive sensitivity to painful stimuli.

group.rdfs_comment: Excessive startle reaction when startled by touch or loud noise.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: an excessive startle reaction (eye blinking or body spasms) to sudden unexpected noise, movement, or touch.
Excessive movement of muscles of the body as a whole, which may be associated with organic or psychological disorders.
Overshooting the target on rapid-alternating-movements.
Hyper Motor Seizures [HMS] are characterized by complex high amplitude movements involving proximal segments of the body resulting violent and inappropriate to the context.
Hyperreflexia is the presence of hyperactive stretch reflexes of the muscles.

A condition in which there is an abnormally increased distance between two organs or bodily parts; most often, this term is referring to an increased distance between the orbits (orbital hypertelorism).

Persistently high systemic arterial BLOOD PRESSURE. Based on multiple readings (BLOOD PRESSURE DETERMINATION), hypertension is currently defined as when SYSTOLIC PRESSURE is consistently greater than 140 mm Hg or when DIASTOLIC PRESSURE is consistently 90 mm Hg or more.
abnormal increase in skeletal or smooth muscle tone; skeletal muscle hypertonicity may be associated with pyramidal tract lesions or basal ganglia diseases.
Hypertrophy of the lower leg and calf muscles.

group.rdfs_comment: Enlargement of sternocleidomastoid muscle in neck.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Hypertrophy of the sternocleidomastoid muscle.
A type of strabismus characterized by permanent upward deviation of the visual axis of one eye.
Diminished sensation in one or more modality including temperature sense, vibration sense, pain sense, light touch sense, or proprioception.
Hypnagogic hallucinations are sleep-related hallucinations that occur while falling asleep.

Abnormally diminished motor activity. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.

A less severe form of mania characterized by elevated mood, hyperactivity, and grandiosity. In contrast to mania, these symptoms do not cause significant impairment of the individual's productivity at work, or social and family relationships.

Hypomelanotic macules (ash leaf spots") are white or lighter patches of skin that may appear anywhere on the body and are caused by a lack of melanin. White ash leaf-shaped macules are considered to be characteristic of tuberous sclerosis.
Undershooting the target on rapid alternating movements.

Normal subjects usually make small amplitude refixations without a discernible aundershoot or overshoot ("normometric" saccades). As the amplitude of the refixation increases, there is a proportional increase in the amount of undershooting which is usually less than 2 degrees and followed by a small corrective movement, referred to as physiologic undershoots. Unusual eye movements consisting of three or more steps, or two steps of approximately equal magnitude, have been called "fragmented," "hypometric," or "stepwise" refixations.
Reduced intensity (volume) of speech.
Decreased but not necessarily absent deep tendon reflexes.
Decreased ability to smell.
Diminution of the skeletal muscle tone marked by a diminished resistance to passive stretching.
Blindness without known physical cause and believed due to a dissociative disorder.
Bizarre gait seen with hysteria-conversion reaction. While walking the foot is usually dragged or pushed ahead, instead of lifted. Frequently the foot is held dorsiflexed and inverted.
Hysterical mutism is a disorder of the vocal function without changing the integrity of the body, resulting in loss of voice.

Hysterical paralysis, a type of adult conversion reaction, although uncommon, is seen occasionally by the spinal surgeon. This disorder involves a nonorganic loss of motor or sensory function that cannot be explained by a physical disorder, but resembles the symptoms of a structural disease of the nervous system.
Jaundice, also known as icterus, is a yellowish or greenish pigmentation of the skin and whites of the eyes due to high bilirubin levels.
Behaviior that is abnormally immature or childish in nature.

Ability to think abstractly is often contrasted with concrete thinking.  Abstraction allows individuals to identify underlying themes and concepts in objects such as how is a chair like a table, a penny like a dollar, honesty like integrity.
A state of decreased responsiveness.
The anal wink, anal reflex, perineal reflex, or anocutaneous reflex is the reflexive contraction of the external anal sphincter upon stroking of the skin around the anus.
An abnormally reduced ankle reflex.
An inability to rise up, usually from a sitting position.
Reduce swing of the arm while walking.
A state of reduced attentiveness to stimuli or the environment.
A deficit in equilibrium, which may manifest as unsteady ambulation or inability to maintain an upright position. (NCI)
Reduction in the strength of the biceps reflex which is elicited by tapping the biceps tendon in the antecubital fossae.
A reduced rate of blinking.
Inability to sense the position of the body using proprioceptors.
An abnormal reduction in the ability to masticate (chew), i.e., in the ability to crush and ground food in preparation for swallowing
Diminished or impaired mental and/or intellectual function.
An anomaly in the ability to discriminate between or recognize colors.
Being unable to focus one's attention or mental effort on a particular object or activity.
A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position occuring at distal joints.

The levator veli palatini muscle emerges from the eustachian tube and the petrous temporal bone before attaching to the palatine aponeurosis, this muscle functions to elevate the soft palate during swallowing to prevent the entry of food into the nasopharynx. Impairment in this process causes a failure to elevate the soft palate.  The soft palate is moveable, consisting of muscle fibers sheathed in mucous membrane. It is responsible for closing off the nasal passages during the act of swallowing, and also for closing off the airway. During sneezing, it protects the nasal passage by diverting a portion of the excreted substance to the mouth. In humans, the uvula hangs from the end of the soft palate. Touching the uvula or the end of the soft palate evokes a strong gag reflex in most people.
Reduced ability to withstand or participate in activities that induce physical or mental exertion.
pathologic process affecting the voluntary or reflex-controlled movements of the eye.

Abnormality on the finger to nose test. Point-to-Point Movement Evaluation, Ask the patient to extend their index finger and touch their nose, and then touch the examiner's outstretched finger with the same finger. Ask the patient to go back and forth between touching their nose and examiner's finger. Once this is done correctly a few times at a moderate cadence, ask the patient to continue with their eyes closed. Normally this movement remains accurate when the eyes are closed. Repeat and compare to the other hand.

The corneal reflex, also known as the blink reflex, is an involuntary blinking of the eyelids elicited by stimulation of the cornea (such as by touching or by a foreign body), though could result from any peripheral stimulus.

group.rdfs_comment: Continued blinking of the eyes when tapping the glabella
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: The glabellar reflex, also known as the "glabellar tap sign", is a primitive reflex elicited by repetitive tapping on the forehead.[1] Subjects blink in response to the first several taps. If the blinking persists, this is known as Myerson's sign, and is abnormal and a sign of frontal release; it is often seen in people who have Parkinson's disease
Difficulty in using hands for tasks that require dexterity and accuracy of movements.
A general term for the complete or partial loss of the ability to hear from one or both ears.

Insight is the ability of patients to see themselves as they are.  When insight is impaired patients may fail to recognize their own neurological deficits such as hemiplegia, amnesia, or even blindness.
Loss of ability to sense joint position using proprioceptors.
Judgment refers to the patient's capacity to make sound, reasoned and responsible decisions.
Reduced reflex at knee upon tapping on the quadriceps tendon.
Failure to retrieve memories from longterm memory or failure to add new memories to long term memory.
Decreased reflexes at the knee and ankle.
Loss of memory.
Impaired movement of the tongue due to weakness.
Loss of joint or position sense, inability to sense the position of a joint using proprioceptive sensors.
Lacking the executive capacity to organize and plan.
Decreased sensation to pain and temperature in the distribution of the radial nerve.
Decreased sensation to pain and temperature in the leg.
Decreased pain and temperature sensation in the distribution of the median nerve.
Decreased pain and temperature sensation in the distribution of the ulnar nerve.
Loss of proprioception at the knees, ankle, and toes.
Failure to register stimuli in working memory.

Impaired eye movements involved in directed gaze. Saccades are rapid eye movements designed to shift the fovea to objects of visual interest. Abnormalities of saccades offer important clues in the diagnosis of a number of movement disorders.

group.rdfs_comment: Loss of sensation in the perineal area.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Loss of sensation in the perineal and groin areas.
Failure to retrieve memories from short term memory, usually measured in minutes to hours.

When the patient is tracking your finger, the eyes should move smoothly (known as ‘smooth pursuit’). In cerebellar lesions, pursuit can be “jerky” or “saccadic”( i.e. made up of lots of small movements).
Findings of speech (excluding aphasia) include altered volume, altered articulation, altered prosody, and altered fluency.
An impairment in the ease with which speech is generated.  Non fluent speech is hestitant and halting and lacks an easy flow of words.
Reduced radial or supinator reflex.
An inability to swallow liquids and solids properly.

group.rdfs_comment: Unable to walk a straight line heel to toe.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Reduced ability to walk in a straight line while placing the feet heal to toe
A decreased triceps reflex.
An inability to turn the body easily while walking.
Reduction of reflexes in the arm including the biceps reflex, triceps reflex, and supinator reflex.
Reduced ability to sense vibration in the feet.  Often tested with a tuning fork.
Decreased vibration sensation in the hands.

A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to bony prominences such as the malleoli at the ankles or the metacarpal-phalangeal joints. There is a slow decay of vibration from the tuning fork. The degree of vibratory sense loss can be crudely estimated by counting the number of seconds that the examiner can perceive the vibration longer than the patient.
A reduction in the ability to maintain sustained attention characterized by reduced altertness. Lack of vigilance, inability to be alertly watchful, especially for danger.
A reduction in visual acuity or visual fields.
Diminished clarity of vision
A reduction in the ability to focus attention on a task or object.
having or showing a tendency to be quickly irritated or provoked.
Inability to develop or maintain an erection of the penis.
Behavior characterized by reduced control
Incapability to ambulate.

group.rdfs_comment: behaving in a peculiar or socially in appropriate way
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: The definition of inappropriate is someone or something that is not within the bounds of what is considered appropriate or socially acceptable.
Using humor and joking inappropriately, usually in the setting of disinhibition due to frontal lobe injury.  See also witzelsucht.
Uncontrolled episodes of crying or laughing, without apparent motivating stimuli.
failure to pay attention
Speech which is non-sensical and difficulty to understand.  This term is used and generally and does not have a precise neurological definition to describe rambling non-sensical speech.
lack of coordination, especially the inability to use different parts of the body together smoothly and efficiently.

An abnormally increased head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart
group.rdfs_seeAlso: Increased head circumference; enlarged head; head size large; large head; Large skull

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Tone is increased in legs.
A traumatic injury to cervical spine involving the vertebral column or spinal cord.
An injury to the lumbar spine involving either the vertebral column or lumbosacral nerve plexus.
Traumatic injury to the thoracic spine with injury to either the thoracic spinal cord or the vertebral spinal column.
A disorder characterized by difficulty in falling asleep and/or remaining asleep.

An abnormality of conjugate lateral gaze in which the affected eye shows impairment of adduction. The pathognomonic clinical sign of internuclear ophthalmoplegia is an impaired adduction while testing horizontal saccades on the side of the lesion in the ipsilateral medial longitudinal fascicule.
Weakness of the intrinsic muscles of the hand
Excessive eye blinking not under voluntary control.
Involuntary contractions of muscle leading to involuntary movements of extremities, neck, trunk, or face.
Abnormal or excessive excitability with easily triggered anger, annoyance, or impatience.

schemic injury to the OPTIC NERVE which usually affects the OPTIC DISK (optic neuropathy, anterior ischemic) and less frequently the retrobulbar portion of the nerve (optic neuropathy, posterior ischemic). The injury results from occlusion of arterial blood supply which may result from TEMPORAL ARTERITIS; ATHEROSCLEROSIS; COLLAGEN DISEASES; EMBOLISM; DIABETES MELLITUS; and other conditions. The disease primarily occurs in the sixth decade or later and presents with the sudden onset of painless and usually severe monocular visual loss. Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy also features optic disk edema with microhemorrhages. The optic disk appears normal in posterior ischemic optic neuropathy.
An unnatural feeling of strangeness about a person or place that is familiar.
A clinical manifestation of HYPERBILIRUBINEMIA, characterized by the yellowish staining of the SKIN; MUCOUS MEMBRANE; and SCLERA. Clinical jaundice usually is a sign of LIVER dysfunction.
An increased jaw jerk elicited by a gentle tap on the mandible with a reflex hammer.
Jerky body movement is a condition in which a person makes fast movements that they cannot control and that have no purpose. These movements interrupt the person's normal movement or posture.
Instability of mood, prone to rapid changes in mood and affect.
A failure to produce tears.
Deviation of the tongue to one side when the tongue is protruded, the tongue usually deviates to the side that is weak.
Leadpipe rigidity is sustained resistance to passive movement throughout the whole range of motion, with no fluctuations.
a condition giving rise to difficulties in acquiring knowledge and skills to the level expected of those of the same age, especially when not associated with a physical handicap.

group.rdfs_comment: Bruit heard over left carotid artery.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Bruit over left carotid artery.
A partial or incomplete upturning of the great toe upon stimulation of the plantar aspect of the foot leading to an equivocal (inconclusive) plantar response reflex.
Weakness of the left face.
a foot drop of the left foot.
A loss of the left visual field in both eyes.
Bulging forward of the left eye.
Headache on the left side.

The sensation of struggling to remain awake. A condition marked by drowsiness and an unusual lack of energy and mental alertness. It can be caused by many things
Lightheadedness is a feeling of faintness, dizziness, or being close to passing out.
An increase in tone and resistance to passive movement in any limb.
Increased tone and spasticity in a limb.
A limitation in horizontal or vertical eye movements.
A sound substitution error in speaking or naming.

a medical condition, usually resulting from a stroke that damages part of the brainstem, in which the body and most of the facial muscles are paralyzed but consciousness remains and the ability to perform certain eye movements is preserved.
A loss of initiative is often a manifestation of pre-frontal dysfunction and abulia with an inability to initiate actions even on command.
Poor control of movements.
A loss of equilibrium is defined by an inability to stand upright.

The executive functions of the brain are often associated with the pre-frontal cortex and include such activities as planning, organizing, censoring, initiating, persevering, and insight.  Deficits in executive functions include disinhibition, inappropriate jocularity, socially inappropriate behavior, abulia, disorganization, confabulation, impersistence, and perseveration.
A loss of ability to use facial muscles to express emotion.

An impaired ability to sense pain, heat, and cold. Pain is usually tested with a sterile pin with a light prick of the skin.  Temperature sensation can be tested with test tubes filled with water of varying temperatures of by using objects with differing thermal conductivity.
Absence of reflexes in the legs.
An inability to sense temperature.
Weakness involving muscle of the lower face.
Muscular atrophy affecting the lower limb

Increased tone and spasticity in the leg.
Sensory loss in the distribution of a lumbar root.

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Diffuse enlargement of the entire cerebral hemispheres leading to macrocephaly (with or without overlying cortical dysplasia).
A nonspecific feeling of bodily discomfort, fatigue and/or unease.
A disorder characterized by excitement of psychotic proportions manifested by mental and physical hyperactivity, disorganization of behavior and elevation of mood.

Marche à petits pas [maʁʃ a pəti pa] (“gait with little steps”) is a type of gait disorder characterised by an abnormal short stepped gait with upright stance (in strict sense, as opposed to generally stooping short-stepped gait of Parkinson's disease), seen in various neurological (or sometimes muscular) disorders. It can be further differentiated from "Parkinsonian gait" by normal arm swing (as opposed to no arm swing in Parkinsonism). This is associated with frontal lobe white matter lesions.[1]
Hypomimia (masked facies, masking of facies, mask-like facial expression), a medical sign, is a reduced degree of facial expression.
Temporary intermittent failures of memory.

Meningism is a set of symptoms similar to those of meningitis but not caused by meningitis. Whereas meningitis is inflammation of the meninges (membranes that cover the central nervous system), meningism is caused by nonmeningitic irritation of the meninges, usually associated with acute febrile illness,especially in children and adolescents

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Abnormalities of affect or behavior

Subnormal intellectual functioning which originates during the developmental period; multiple potential etiologies, including genetic defects and perinatal insults; intelligence quotient (IQ) scores are commonly used to determine whether an individual is mentally retarded; IQ scores between 70 and 79 are in the borderline mentally retarded range and scores below 67 are in the retarded range.

An abnormality in language, memory, visual-spatial functions, attention, executive functions, or other higher cortical functions such as reading, writing, speaking, recognition, insight, judgment, planning, or abstract thinking.

Classical teaching has associated all lesions of the rostral midbrain with bilateral light-near dissociation (LND), defined as attenuation of the pupil light reflex (PLR) with relative sparing of the near response.
A visual anomaly in which images appear distorted. A grid of straight lines appears wavy and parts of the grid may appear blank.
Abnormally small head.

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Abnormally small sized handwriting defined formally as an impairment of a fine motor skill manifesting mainly as a progressive or stable reduction in amplitude during a writing task.
Migraine headache with an accompanying aura such as visual scintillations.
Dysarthria that is mild in severity.
Facial weakness that is of mild severity.
A memory disturbance that is mild in severity.
Ataxia in the arm that is mild in severity
Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil
unacceptable or improper behavior, especially by an employee or professional person.
Weakness in a single limb.
Complete loss of movement in one limb.
A severe weakness of one arm.
Severe weakness of one leg.
an abrupt and apparently unaccountable change of mood.

This category includes thoughts of killing or injuring others, of having death or injury inflicted on one’s self or loved ones, of acting sexually in ways that are either unnatural to the person or against society’s norms, or finally, thoughts of acting inappropriately in public (e.g. taking off one’s clothes, shouting obscenities, making rude gestures, etc.).
A mental state characterized by frivolity, joviality, and the inability to be serious.  Childish in nature.
A disorder characterized by the inability to convey emotion by using the prosody of speech.
A finding related to the motor system including changes in strength, tone, or muscle bulk.
The inability to continue a motor activity without repeated verbal cues (e.g. "hold your hands outstretched."
Neurological conditions resulting in abnormal voluntary or involuntary movement, which may impact the speed, fluency, quality and ease of movement.

A process, occurring in the muscle, that is characterized by a decrease in protein content, fiber diameter, force production and fatigue resistance in response to different conditions such as starvation, aging and disuse.
Muscle atrophy in the arms.
Muscle atrophy in the deltoid muscle.
Muscle atrophy in the distal forearm and hands.

Muscle atrophy in the distal arm and the hand.

muscle atrophy in the forearm.

Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the legs, i.e., of the thigh.
Muscle atrophy in the shoulder muscles.
Muscle atrophy in the shoulder girdle muscles.
Atrophy of the tongue.
A sudden and involuntary contraction of a muscle muscle, which may be painful.
An abnormal, increased fatiguability of the musculature.
general increase in bulk of a muscle due to an increase in cell volume; it is not due to tumor formation, nor to an increase in the number of cells.
Tenderness of the muscle on palpation.
The occurrence of a single contraction or a series of contractions of a muscle.
Weakness in the proximal muscles of the arms and legs of mild to moderate severity
The inability to generate oral-verbal expression, despite normal comprehension of speech. This may be associated with brain diseases or mental diseases.
Myalgias can be defined as muscle aches. Myalgias can be a deep, constant, dull ache, or a sharp, sporadic ache.
Abnormal dilatation of the iris.

A localized contraction of a degenerating muscle, occurring at the point of a sharp blow, independent of the nerve supply.  Sometimes a small bump occurs on a muscle at the site of a percussion blow.  Myoedema may also occur in uremia and myxedema.

A myoclonic seizure is a type of motor seizure characterised by sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction of muscles or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal).
A rapid, involuntary jerk of a muscle or group of muscles.

group.rdfs_comment: Myoclonic jerk when startled by loud noise.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Its clinical presentation usually consists of an involuntary jerky movement (with blink, contortion of the face, flexion of neck and trunk, and abduction and flexion of the arms) evoked by a sudden and unexpected acoustic stimulus.

group.rdfs_comment: Myokymias are localised involuntary contractions that are wavelike or vermicular and propagate through affected striated muscle
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Myokymia consists of involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions that spread across the affected striated muscle.

group.rdfs_comment: Delayed relaxation of muscle after contraction
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Prolonged failure of muscle relaxation after contraction. This may occur after voluntary contractions, muscle percussion, or electrical stimulation of the muscle.  Myotonia occurs in some myopathies such as myotonia congenita, paramyotonia, certain channelopathies, and some forms of musuclar paralysis related to potassium metabolism.
recurrent, uncontrollable brief episodes of sleep and lapses in consciousness, often associated with hypnagogic hallucinations, cataplexy, automatic behaviors and sleep paralysis

Nasal congestion or "stuffy nose" occurs when nasal and adjacent tissues and blood vessels become swollen with excess fluid, causing a "stuffy" plugged feeling. Nasal congestion may or may not include a nasal discharge or "runny nose."
a feeling of sickness with an inclination to vomit
A physical finding in the neck region such as carotid bruit or neck stiffness.

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Pain that begins in the neck and radiates to an arm.

A sensation of tightness in the neck when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity. Neck stiffness often involves soreness and difficulty moving the neck, especially when trying to turn the head to the side

group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: Inattention to stimuli on one side of the body.

a new word that is coined especially by a person affected with schizophrenia, aphasia, or dementia and is meaningless except to the coiner, and is typically a combination of two existing words or a shortening or distortion of an existing word
Symptoms related to the muscular or nervous system.

group.rdfs_comment: Nightmares are vivid dreams with frightening or unsettling content.
group.rdfs_isDefinedBy: A disturbing dream that occurs during rapid eye movement sleep and results in feelings of strong terror, fear, distress, or anxiety.

involuntary, rapid, rhythmic movement of the eyeball
